The paper deals with user profiling in social media, which involves analyzing user-generated data. This suggests that the paper could belong to several sub-categories, including Social and Information Networks (cs.SI), Computation and Language (cs.CL), Sound and Music Computing (cs.SD), Machine Learning (cs.LG), and Information Retrieval (cs.IR). Among these, cs.SI is the most likely category, as it directly relates to the study of social media and user relationships. cs.CL is also a likely category, as it deals with natural language processing, which is relevant for analyzing user-generated content. cs.SD is less likely, as it is more focused on audio and music data. cs.LG and cs.IR are also relevant, but may be less likely as they are broader categories that encompass a wide range of topics.
